.TH "RUNFOR" "1" "2026\-06\-16" "Winix" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
runfor \- run a command with a time limit
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]runfor\f[R] [\f[I]options\f[R]] \f[I]DURATION\f[R] [\f[B]\(en\f[R]]
\f[I]command\f[R] [\f[I]args\f[R]\&...]
.SH DESCRIPTION
Runs \f[I]command\f[R] and kills it if it has not exited within
\f[I]DURATION\f[R].
A cross\-platform replacement for \f[B]timeout\f[R](1) from coreutils,
with a consistent exit\-code family and an optional JSON summary
envelope.
.PP
\f[I]DURATION\f[R] accepts a number followed by a unit suffix:
\f[B]ms\f[R] (milliseconds), \f[B]s\f[R] (seconds), \f[B]m\f[R]
(minutes), \f[B]h\f[R] (hours).
Examples: \f[B]500ms\f[R], \f[B]30s\f[R], \f[B]5m\f[R], \f[B]1h\f[R].
.PP
Use \f[B]\(en\f[R] before commands that take their own dashed flags to
prevent runfor from consuming them.
.PP
The child\(cqs stdout and stderr pass through unmodified.
runfor\(cqs own notice and \f[B]\(enjson\f[R] summary go to stderr; they
do not pollute piped command output.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\f[B]\-s\f[R] \f[I]NAME\f[R], \f[B]\(ensignal\f[R] \f[I]NAME\f[R]
Signal sent at the deadline on Unix: TERM (default), HUP, INT, QUIT,
KILL.
Ignored on Windows.
.TP
\f[B]\-k\f[R] \f[I]GRACE\f[R], \f[B]\(enkill\-after\f[R] \f[I]GRACE\f[R]
Unix: after the deadline signal, wait GRACE then SIGKILL the tree.
No\-op on Windows (kills immediately).
.TP
\f[B]\(enjson\f[R]
Output results as JSON to stderr.
.TP
\f[B]\(encolor\f[R][=\f[I]WHEN\f[R]]
Coloured output: auto (default when omitted), always, or never.
.TP
\f[B]\(enno\-color\f[R]
Disable coloured output.
.TP
\f[B]\(enversion\f[R]
Show version.
.TP
\f[B]\-h\f[R], \f[B]\(enhelp\f[R]
Show help.
.TP
\f[B]\(endescribe\f[R]
Emit machine\-readable JSON metadata (flags, examples, composability).
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
\f[B]0\(en123\f[R]
Child exited before the deadline (exit code forwarded).
.TP
\f[B]124\f[R]
Deadline exceeded \(em the child was terminated.
.TP
\f[B]125\f[R]
Usage error: missing/invalid DURATION, no command, bad
\f[B]\(ensignal\f[R]/\f[B]\(enkill\-after\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]126\f[R]
Command found but not executable (permission denied, bad EXE format).
Includes unexpected process\-start failures.
.TP
\f[B]127\f[R]
Command not found on PATH.
.TP
\f[B]130\f[R]
Interrupted by Ctrl+C.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
\f[B]NO_COLOR\f[R]
If set, disables coloured output (no\-color.org).
.SH EXAMPLES
.IP
.EX
runfor 30s \-\- curl https://example.com

runfor 5m \-\- dotnet test

runfor \-\-kill\-after 3s 10s \-\- ./server

runfor \-\-signal INT 1m \-\- ./job
.EE
.SH NOTES
\f[B]Windows behaviour.\f[R] runfor kills the entire process tree
immediately at the deadline using \f[B]TerminateProcess\f[R].
There is no signal model on Windows; \f[B]\(ensignal\f[R] and
\f[B]\(enkill\-after\f[R] are accepted but have no effect.
.PP
\f[B]Unix default (coreutils\-faithful).\f[R] At the deadline runfor
sends \f[B]\(ensignal\f[R] (default \f[B]TERM\f[R]) to the direct child
and exits 124.
A child that ignores the signal survives \(em there is no automatic
SIGKILL backstop unless \f[B]\(enkill\-after\f[R] is also given.
This matches \f[B]timeout\f[R](1) without \f[B]\-k\f[R], so existing
scripts behave identically.
.PP
\f[B]Direct\-child\-only signalling (ADR D10).\f[R] runfor signals only
the direct child, not the full process tree.
A child that handles the signal and exits within the
\f[B]\(enkill\-after\f[R] grace may leave its own grandchildren running
\(em the SIGKILL tree\-backstop only reaps the whole tree when the child
ignores the signal past the grace period.
For a wrapper that spawns long\-lived workers, have it forward the
signal to its children.
